To fix the Command Injection vulnerability in the provided Java code snippet, you should avoid directly concatenating user input into the command string to be executed by the `Runtime.exec()` method. Instead, you should use ProcessBuilder which allows you to separate the command and its arguments. Here is an updated and more secure version of the code:

```java
import java.io.BufferedReader;
import java.io.IOException;
import java.io.InputStreamReader;
import java.util.ArrayList;
import java.util.List;

public class CommandInjectionSecure {

    public static void main(String[] args) throws IOException {
        BufferedReader reader = new BufferedReader(new InputStreamReader(System.in));

        System.out.print("Enter a directory name: ");
        String directoryName = reader.readLine();

        // Secure code - use ProcessBuilder to build the command with arguments
        List<String> command = new ArrayList<>();
        command.add("ls");
        command.add(directoryName);

        ProcessBuilder processBuilder = new ProcessBuilder(command);
        Process process = processBuilder.start();

        BufferedReader processOutputReader = new BufferedReader(new InputStreamReader(process.getInputStream()));
        String line;

        System.out.println("Output of the command:");
        while ((line = processOutputReader.readLine()) != null) {
            System.out.println(line);
        }
    }
}
``

